1
00:00:06,715 --> 00:00:09,551
WOMAN: (ON TV) Orchestrations
were arranged by Sir Rhodri Fenning

2
00:00:09,635 --> 00:00:13,096
and Dame Evelyn Blish is a member
of the Kings Lynn players.

3
00:00:13,680 --> 00:00:18,268
So tune in again next week for more
from the What's My Line? team.

4
00:00:18,727 --> 00:00:22,064
And that brings us to the end
of programming for today.

5
00:00:22,648 --> 00:00:27,694
So, from all of us here at Alexandra Palace,
a very good night.

6
00:00:30,447 --> 00:00:32,991
£200 overdrawn.

7
00:00:36,745 --> 00:00:38,789
I need a miracle.

8
00:00:46,046 --> 00:00:48,298
(PEOPLE LAUGHING)

9
00:00:48,382 --> 00:00:50,467
(RAIN PATTERING)

10
00:00:52,052 --> 00:00:54,471
(CHATTER ON THE RADIO)

11
00:00:54,555 --> 00:00:57,599
He's a caution, that one.
He does make me laugh.

12
00:00:58,809 --> 00:01:01,353
Oh, our lord and master.

13
00:01:01,478 --> 00:01:03,772
-Rita, I'm off out.
-Dad.

14
00:01:04,439 --> 00:01:07,192
Oh, how many times, son? We'll see.

15
00:01:07,276 --> 00:01:10,153
But everyone's getting a telly, Dad,
even Mr Gallagher.

16
00:01:10,279 --> 00:01:12,573
And the Bells at number 67.

17
00:01:13,323 --> 00:01:15,659
Well, perhaps we'll get one
for the Coronation.

18
00:01:15,742 --> 00:01:18,287
If you're lucky. We'll see.

19
00:01:19,037 --> 00:01:20,414
Don't wait up.

20
00:01:20,497 --> 00:01:24,126
I heard they rot your brains.
Rot them into soup

21
00:01:24,209 --> 00:01:27,337
and your brain comes pouring
out of your ears.

22
00:01:27,421 --> 00:01:29,298
That's what television does.

23
00:01:52,529 --> 00:01:53,905
Mr Magpie?

24
00:01:54,573 --> 00:01:56,950
-Oh , Mr Magpie?
-Eh?.

25
00:01:58,327 --> 00:02:01,496
-Whoo-hoo! Can you hear me, Magpie?
-Yes.

26
00:02:04,625 --> 00:02:07,711
-I must be dreaming.
-Oh, no. This isn't a dream.

27
00:02:08,211 --> 00:02:11,548
-I'm going doolally, then.
-Not at all sweetheart.

28
00:02:11,673 --> 00:02:14,926
Now, are you sitting comfortably?

29
00:02:15,344 --> 00:02:18,180
Good, then we'll begin.

30
00:02:20,807 --> 00:02:23,268
(WOMAN LAUGHING)

31
00:02:23,352 --> 00:02:26,063
(MAGPIE GROANING)

32
00:02:31,985 --> 00:02:34,279
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

33
00:03:16,279 --> 00:03:19,032
I thought we'd be going for the Vegas era.

34
00:03:19,116 --> 00:03:22,285
You know, the white flares
and the chest hair.

35
00:03:22,369 --> 00:03:24,121
You are kidding, aren't you?

36
00:03:24,204 --> 00:03:26,331
If you wanna see Elvis,
you go for the late '50s.

37
00:03:26,456 --> 00:03:28,166
The time before burgers!

38
00:03:28,250 --> 00:03:30,961
When they called him "The Pelvis"
and he still had a waist!

39
00:03:31,044 --> 00:03:33,255
What's more, you see him in style!

40
00:03:41,513 --> 00:03:43,306
(IMITATING ELVIS) You going my way, doll?

41
00:03:43,473 --> 00:03:47,686
Is there any other way to go, daddy-o?
Straight from the fridge, man!

42
00:03:48,061 --> 00:03:50,272
Hey, you speak the lingo!

43
00:03:50,355 --> 00:03:54,985
Yeah, well, me and Mum, Cliff Richard
movies every Bank Holiday Monday.

44
00:03:55,110 --> 00:03:58,113
cliff! I knew your mother
would be a cliff fan.

45
00:04:02,159 --> 00:04:05,328
-Where we off to?
-Ed Sullivan TV studios.

46
00:04:05,454 --> 00:04:08,498
Elvis did Hound Dog on one of the shows.
There were loads of complaints.

47
00:04:08,665 --> 00:04:10,500
Bit of luck, we'll just catch it.

48
00:04:10,584 --> 00:04:14,755
And that would be the TV studios in,
what, New York?

49
00:04:14,838 --> 00:04:16,214
That's the one!

50
00:04:20,135 --> 00:04:21,678
(ROSE LAUGHING)

51
00:04:21,803 --> 00:04:23,764
Digging that New York vibe!

52
00:04:23,847 --> 00:04:28,977
Well, this could still be New York.
I mean, this looks very New York to me.

53
00:04:30,687 --> 00:04:34,441
-London-y New York, mind, but...
-What are all the flags for?

54
00:04:38,195 --> 00:04:40,697
(MUFFIN THE MULE THEME ON TV)

55
00:04:44,826 --> 00:04:49,873
Smashing! Smashing, innit?

56
00:04:51,124 --> 00:04:53,794
You'd have thought
they was in the room with ya, eh?

57
00:04:53,877 --> 00:04:57,714
Fair do's, Tommy, you had a point.
New television.

58
00:04:58,548 --> 00:05:02,761
There, that should cheer you up a bit, Rita?
Give us a smile, then, eh?

59
00:05:02,844 --> 00:05:05,847
I can't. Nothing's the same anymore.
Not with her...

60
00:05:05,931 --> 00:05:08,934
-Stop going on about it!
-But her face, Eddie.

61
00:05:09,851 --> 00:05:13,063
What happened to her? That awful face.

62
00:05:13,146 --> 00:05:14,898
I said stop it!

63
00:05:14,981 --> 00:05:17,609
(THUMPING)

64
00:05:20,570 --> 00:05:24,991
She's awake. I think she's hungry.

65
00:05:25,909 --> 00:05:29,830
There you go, sir.
All wired up for the great occasion.

66
00:05:29,913 --> 00:05:31,915
Great occasion? What do you mean?

67
00:05:31,998 --> 00:05:34,709
Where you been living, out in the colonies?

68
00:05:34,793 --> 00:05:36,962
The Coronation of course!

69
00:05:37,045 --> 00:05:39,256
And what Coronation's that, then?

70
00:05:39,548 --> 00:05:42,175
What do you mean? The Coronation!

71
00:05:42,717 --> 00:05:45,720
It's the Queen's! Queen Elizabeth!

72
00:05:46,763 --> 00:05:50,600
-Oh! Is this 19537
-Last time I looked.

73
00:05:50,767 --> 00:05:54,229
Time for a lovely bit of
pomp and circumstance. What we do best.

74
00:05:54,312 --> 00:05:57,899
Look at all the TV aerials.
Looks like everyone's got one.

75
00:05:58,024 --> 00:06:02,028
That's weird. My mum said tellies were
so rare, they all had to pile into one house.

76
00:06:02,112 --> 00:06:05,115
Not round here, love.
Magpie's Marvellous Tellies.

77
00:06:05,240 --> 00:06:09,369
-Only five quid a pop!
-Oh, but this is a brilliant year, classic!

78
00:06:10,120 --> 00:06:15,083
Technicolor! Everest climbed!
Everything off the ration!

79
00:06:15,166 --> 00:06:17,502
A nation throwing off the shackles of war

80
00:06:17,627 --> 00:06:20,505
and looking forward to a happier,
brighter future!

81
00:06:20,839 --> 00:06:23,675
WOMAN: Someone help me, please! Ted!

82
00:06:23,758 --> 00:06:26,219
Leave him alone! That's my husband!

83
00:06:26,303 --> 00:06:28,638
-WOMAN: Please!
-What's going on?

84
00:06:29,681 --> 00:06:33,268
-0i! What are you doing?
-Police business. Get out of the way, sir.

85
00:06:33,351 --> 00:06:37,063
-Who did they take? Do you know him?
-Must be Mr Gallagher.

86
00:06:40,483 --> 00:06:44,029
It's happening all over the place.
They're turning into monsters.

87
00:06:44,112 --> 00:06:47,991
Tommy! Not one word. Get inside now!

88
00:06:48,158 --> 00:06:50,577
Sorry, I'd better do as he says.

89
00:06:57,542 --> 00:06:59,794
DOCTOR: All aboard!

90
00:07:02,881 --> 00:07:05,926
Operation Market Stall. Go! Go! Go!

91
00:07:24,527 --> 00:07:28,281
Lost them. How did they get away from us?

92
00:07:28,365 --> 00:07:30,951
I'm surprised they didn't turn back
and arrest you for reckless driving.

93
00:07:31,034 --> 00:07:32,869
Have you actually passed your test?

94
00:07:32,953 --> 00:07:35,747
Men in black? Vanishing police cars?

95
00:07:35,872 --> 00:07:38,708
This is Churchill's England,
not Stalin's Russia.

96
00:07:39,417 --> 00:07:41,461
Monsters, that boy said.

97
00:07:42,462 --> 00:07:44,506
Maybe we should go and ask
the neighbours.

98
00:07:44,589 --> 00:07:47,801
That's what I like about you,
the domestic approach.

99
00:07:47,884 --> 00:07:49,427
Thank you.

100
00:07:50,428 --> 00:07:52,389
Hold on. Was that an insult?

101
00:07:56,226 --> 00:07:59,729
MAGPIE: I've finished it as you instructed.

102
00:08:02,148 --> 00:08:06,236
-That's awfully good of you, Mr Magpie.
-So you'll go soon?

103
00:08:06,528 --> 00:08:09,781
-You'll leave me?
-We'll see.

104
00:08:10,532 --> 00:08:12,492
If you're a very good boy.

105
00:08:12,575 --> 00:08:16,997
Please. You're burning me. Inside.

106
00:08:17,205 --> 00:08:20,417
Behind my eyes. It hurts.

107
00:08:20,917 --> 00:08:23,086
Even my memories hurt.

108
00:08:23,169 --> 00:08:25,714
I just want things
back like they used to be.

109
00:08:25,797 --> 00:08:29,968
Oh, but this world of yours
is busy, busy, busy,

110
00:08:30,051 --> 00:08:33,179
forging ahead into a brand-new age.

111
00:08:33,346 --> 00:08:36,933
You can never go back. That's your tragedy.

112
00:08:37,684 --> 00:08:42,397
But now the time is almost ripe, Magpie.

113
00:08:43,106 --> 00:08:46,484
Cometh the hour, cometh the man.

114
00:08:49,863 --> 00:08:51,531
Or lady.

115
00:08:58,038 --> 00:09:00,331
(STAIRS CREAKING)

116
00:09:01,041 --> 00:09:04,169
(THUDDING)

117
00:09:17,307 --> 00:09:21,728
Gran? Gran, it's me. It's Tommy.

118
00:09:22,979 --> 00:09:25,231
I'm gonna come in, Gran.

119
00:09:25,315 --> 00:09:28,610
Stand back. Just don't...

120
00:09:30,278 --> 00:09:34,616
-I'm sorry, but I've got to come in.
-What do you think you're doing?

121
00:09:34,699 --> 00:09:37,285
We gotta try and help her, Dad.

122
00:09:37,368 --> 00:09:38,995
Give me that key.

123
00:09:40,538 --> 00:09:43,708
I said give me that key right now.

124
00:09:49,506 --> 00:09:52,217
And don't think I've finished with you.

125
00:09:52,467 --> 00:09:55,303
All the warnings I've given you
and every time,

126
00:09:55,386 --> 00:09:58,640
every time, you disobey me.

127
00:09:58,723 --> 00:10:03,061
-We can't just lock her away.
-Excuse me, sunshine, I am talking.

128
00:10:03,520 --> 00:10:06,106
And you can forget that college nonsense.

129
00:10:06,189 --> 00:10:08,399
You're gonna come and work alongside me.

130
00:10:08,483 --> 00:10:10,443
Get your hands dirty for once.

131
00:10:10,527 --> 00:10:11,736
(THUDDING)

132
00:10:11,820 --> 00:10:14,239
Oh, Lord! Won't she ever stop?

133
00:10:16,574 --> 00:10:20,870
There, there, Rita, my sweet.
Business as usual.

134
00:10:21,621 --> 00:10:25,875
Now, let's get these up all over the house
in honour of Her Majesty.

135
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:28,253
But, Eddie, what if she's dying?

136
00:10:28,378 --> 00:10:30,505
I am talking!

137
00:10:31,881 --> 00:10:34,676
(SCOOTER ENGINE HUMMING)

138
00:10:36,427 --> 00:10:38,054
That's better.

139
00:10:38,555 --> 00:10:40,265
A little bit of hush.

140
00:10:40,348 --> 00:10:42,559
(DOORBELL RINGING)

141
00:10:44,727 --> 00:10:46,729
-Hi!
-Hi!

142
00:10:46,813 --> 00:10:48,481
Who are you, then?

143
00:10:48,565 --> 00:10:51,609
Let's see, judging by the look of you,
family man, nice house, decent wage,

144
00:10:51,693 --> 00:10:54,070
fought in the war, therefore,
I represent Queen and country!

145
00:10:54,154 --> 00:10:57,157
Just doing a check of her forthcoming
Majesty's subjects before the great day.

146
00:10:57,240 --> 00:11:00,243
Don't mind if we come in?
No, I didn't think you did. Thank you.

147
00:11:00,326 --> 00:11:02,912
Not bad, very nice, very well kept.

148
00:11:02,996 --> 00:11:05,456
-I'd like to congratulate you, Mrs...?
-Connolly.

149
00:11:05,540 --> 00:11:07,292
Now then, Rita. I can handle this.

150
00:11:07,417 --> 00:11:11,671
This gentleman's a proper representative.
Don't mind the wife. She rattles on a bit.

151
00:11:11,754 --> 00:11:13,882
Well, maybe she should rattle on
a bit more.

152
00:11:13,965 --> 00:11:16,426
I'm not convinced you're doing
your patriotic duty.

153
00:11:16,509 --> 00:11:19,137
Those flags, why are they not flying?

154
00:11:20,054 --> 00:11:23,433
There we are, Rita, I told you.
Get them up. Queen and country.

155
00:11:23,516 --> 00:11:25,977
-I'm sorry.
-Get it done. Do it now.

156
00:11:26,060 --> 00:11:29,147
-Hold on a minute. Hold on a minute.
-Like the gentleman says...

157
00:11:29,230 --> 00:11:32,025
You've got hands, Mr Connolly.
Two big hands.

158
00:11:32,108 --> 00:11:35,278
-Then why is that your wife's job?
-Well, it's housework, innit?

159
00:11:35,361 --> 00:11:37,864
-And that's a woman's job?
-Course it is.

160
00:11:37,947 --> 00:11:40,783
Mr Connolly, what gender is the Queen?

161
00:11:41,618 --> 00:11:42,869
She's a female.

162
00:11:42,952 --> 00:11:46,080
And are you suggesting the Queen
does the housework?

163
00:11:48,958 --> 00:11:52,587
-No, not at all.
-Then get busy!

164
00:11:53,963 --> 00:11:55,798
Right. Yes, sir.

165
00:11:56,299 --> 00:12:01,304
You'll be proud of us, sir! We'll have
Union Jacks left, right and centre!

166
00:12:01,804 --> 00:12:05,600
Excuse me, Mr Connolly. Hang on a minute.
Union Jacks?

167
00:12:05,725 --> 00:12:08,519
-Yes, that's right, isn't it?
-That's the Union flag.

168
00:12:08,728 --> 00:12:11,397
It's the Union Jack
only when it's flown at sea.

169
00:12:11,481 --> 00:12:14,901
Oh, I'm sorry. I do apologise.

170
00:12:15,026 --> 00:12:18,780
Well, don't get it wrong again.
There's a good man. Now get to it!

171
00:12:22,367 --> 00:12:26,788
Right, then, nice and comfy.
At her Majesty's leisure!

172
00:12:26,955 --> 00:12:29,165
-Union flag?
-Mum went out with a sailor.

173
00:12:29,249 --> 00:12:31,000
(CHUCKLING) I bet she did.

174
00:12:31,125 --> 00:12:34,254
Anyway, I'm the Doctor and this is Rose.
And you are?

175
00:12:34,837 --> 00:12:37,423
-Tommy.
-Well, sit yourself down, Tommy.

176
00:12:39,008 --> 00:12:42,804
Have a look at this. I love telly, don't you?

177
00:12:42,887 --> 00:12:45,390
-Yeah, I think it's brilliant.
-Good man.

178
00:12:47,684 --> 00:12:49,435
Keep working, Mr C!

179
00:12:49,560 --> 00:12:52,480
Now, why don't you tell me what's wrong?

180
00:12:53,398 --> 00:12:56,276
-Did you say you were a doctor?
-Yes, I am.

181
00:12:56,985 --> 00:13:01,531
Can you help her? Oh, please.
Can you help her, Doctor?

182
00:13:01,614 --> 00:13:04,242
Now then, Rita, I don't think
the gentleman needs to know.

183
00:13:04,325 --> 00:13:08,329
-Oh, the gentleman does.
-Tell us what's wrong, and we can help.

184
00:13:09,706 --> 00:13:12,375
It's all right. It's all right. Come here.

185
00:13:13,418 --> 00:13:15,586
Oh, its okay. It's all right.

186
00:13:16,754 --> 00:13:18,464
Hold on a minute.

187
00:13:19,257 --> 00:13:22,302
Queen and Country's one thing,
but this is my house.

188
00:13:22,719 --> 00:13:25,263
What the... What the hell am I doing?

189
00:13:26,055 --> 00:13:30,059
Now you listen here, Doctor.
You may have fancy qualifications,

190
00:13:30,143 --> 00:13:33,271
but what goes on under my roof
is my business.

191
00:13:33,396 --> 00:13:36,441
-Not if people are being bundled into...
-I am talking!

192
00:13:36,649 --> 00:13:39,777
And I'm not listening!

193
00:13:39,902 --> 00:13:41,321
Now you, Mr Connolly,

194
00:13:41,404 --> 00:13:44,449
you are staring into a deep, dark pit
of trouble if you don't let me help.

195
00:13:44,532 --> 00:13:48,036
So I'm ordering you, sir,
tell me what's going on!

196
00:13:48,161 --> 00:13:50,705
(THUDDING)

197
00:13:54,625 --> 00:13:56,294
She won't stop.

198
00:13:56,794 --> 00:13:58,338
(THUDDING CONTINUES)

199
00:13:59,297 --> 00:14:00,965
She never stops.

200
00:14:02,091 --> 00:14:05,470
We started hearing stories,
all round the place.

201
00:14:05,762 --> 00:14:08,097
People who have changed.

202
00:14:08,222 --> 00:14:11,184
Families keeping it secret
'cause they were scared.

203
00:14:11,267 --> 00:14:14,687
Then the police started finding out.
We don't know how, no one does.

204
00:14:14,771 --> 00:14:18,107
They just turn up.
They come to the door and take them.

205
00:14:18,191 --> 00:14:20,151
Any time of the day or night.

206
00:14:20,234 --> 00:14:21,277
Show me.

207
00:14:22,945 --> 00:14:24,947
(DOOR CREAKING)

208
00:14:26,574 --> 00:14:29,577
Gran, it's Tommy.

209
00:14:30,119 --> 00:14:32,330
It's all right, Gran. I've brought help.

210
00:14:33,414 --> 00:14:35,792
(FLOORBOARDS CREAKING)

211
00:14:47,637 --> 00:14:50,264
Her face has completely gone.

212
00:14:52,725 --> 00:14:54,936
Scarcely an electrical impulse left.

213
00:14:55,019 --> 00:14:58,022
Almost complete neural shutdown.
It's just ticking over.

214
00:14:59,232 --> 00:15:03,444
It's like her brain's been wiped clean.

215
00:15:03,528 --> 00:15:06,614
What are we gonna do, Doctor?
We can't even feed her.

216
00:15:07,698 --> 00:15:09,909
-We've got company!
-It's them. They've come for her!

217
00:15:09,992 --> 00:15:12,328
What was she doing before this happened?
Where was she?

218
00:15:12,412 --> 00:15:15,373
-Tell me, quickly, think!
-I can't think. She doesn't leave the house.

219
00:15:15,456 --> 00:15:17,708
-She was just...
-Hold on a minute!

220
00:15:17,834 --> 00:15:20,962
There are three important,
brilliant and complicated reasons

221
00:15:21,045 --> 00:15:22,588
why you should listen to me.

222
00:15:22,672 --> 00:15:24,715
-One...
-Doctor!

223
00:15:26,008 --> 00:15:29,095
Leave her alone. You'll hurt her! Mum!

224
00:15:29,554 --> 00:15:32,140
Come back. Don't hurt her.

225
00:15:32,849 --> 00:15:35,059
-Back inside, Rita.
-She's my mother!

226
00:15:35,143 --> 00:15:36,811
Back inside now, I said!

227
00:15:36,894 --> 00:15:38,938
(CRYING)

228
00:15:39,021 --> 00:15:42,650
Hell of a right hook.
Have to watch out for that.

229
00:15:46,821 --> 00:15:49,449
Don't fight it. Back inside.

230
00:15:49,532 --> 00:15:51,951
-Rose, come on!
-EDDIE: Get back inside.

231
00:15:52,660 --> 00:15:54,871
TOMMY: But they took her.
EDDIE: Don't fight it.

232
00:15:54,996 --> 00:15:57,206
Rose! We're gonna lose them again!

233
00:16:00,293 --> 00:16:02,503
But they took her!
That was Gran and they took her!

234
00:16:02,587 --> 00:16:05,173
EDDIE: Come on, back inside, lad.

235
00:16:12,889 --> 00:16:16,184
TOMMY: How did they know?
How did they find her? Who told them?

236
00:16:17,310 --> 00:16:20,855
You! Get the hell out of my house!

237
00:16:20,938 --> 00:16:24,859
I'm going. I'm done.
Nice to meet you, Tommy.

238
00:16:25,318 --> 00:16:27,278
Mrs Connolly.

239
00:16:28,070 --> 00:16:30,364
And as for you, Mr Connolly,

240
00:16:30,448 --> 00:16:33,367
only an idiot hangs
the Union flag upside down.

241
00:16:33,826 --> 00:16:35,745
Shame on you.

242
00:16:59,602 --> 00:17:01,562
Oh, very good.

243
00:17:03,940 --> 00:17:06,734
Very good.

244
00:19:20,618 --> 00:19:22,745
Stay where you are!

245
00:19:26,749 --> 00:19:31,295
I'm sorry, miss. I'm afraid you're too late.
I was just about to lock the door.

246
00:19:31,754 --> 00:19:33,756
Yeah? Well, I wanna buy a telly.

247
00:19:33,839 --> 00:19:37,635
-Come back tomorrow, please.
-You'll be closed, won't you?

248
00:19:38,594 --> 00:19:41,097
-What?
-For the big day?

249
00:19:41,931 --> 00:19:46,769
-The Coronation?
-Yes, yes, of course. The big day.

250
00:19:48,979 --> 00:19:52,441
I'm sure you'll find somewhere to watch it.
Please go.

251
00:19:52,608 --> 00:19:55,319
Seems to me
half of London's got a television,

252
00:19:55,444 --> 00:19:57,863
since you're practically giving them away.

253
00:19:57,947 --> 00:20:01,701
-I have my reasons.
-And what are they?

254
00:20:02,368 --> 00:20:04,453
(STATIC)

255
00:20:06,205 --> 00:20:08,040
Hungry!

256
00:20:09,125 --> 00:20:10,209
Hungry!

257
00:20:10,292 --> 00:20:13,379
-What's that?
-It's just the television.

258
00:20:13,462 --> 00:20:16,173
One of these modern programmes.

259
00:20:16,257 --> 00:20:20,219
Now, I really do think
you should leave right now.

260
00:20:21,470 --> 00:20:25,641
Not until you've answered my questions.
How comes your televisions are so cheap?

261
00:20:25,725 --> 00:20:27,768
It's my patriotic duty.

262
00:20:27,893 --> 00:20:32,106
Seems only right that as many folk
as possible get to watch the Coronation.

263
00:20:32,440 --> 00:20:35,735
We may be losing the Empire,
but we can still be proud!

264
00:20:35,818 --> 00:20:38,320
Twenty million people
they reckon will be watching.

265
00:20:38,446 --> 00:20:41,657
Imagine that.
And 20 million people can't be wrong, eh?

266
00:20:41,782 --> 00:20:45,286
So why don't you get yourself back home
and get up bright and early for the big day?

267
00:20:45,369 --> 00:20:48,080
No, I'm not leaving
till I've seen everything.

268
00:20:48,664 --> 00:20:50,082
I need to close.

269
00:20:53,210 --> 00:20:57,173
Mr Magpie,
something's happening out there.

270
00:20:57,798 --> 00:21:00,509
Ordinary people are being struck down
and changed

271
00:21:00,634 --> 00:21:03,679
and the only new thing in the house
is a television.

272
00:21:04,722 --> 00:21:08,392
Your television. What's going on?

273
00:21:11,187 --> 00:21:12,730
I knew this would happen.

274
00:21:14,190 --> 00:21:16,150
I knew I'd be found out.

275
00:21:27,703 --> 00:21:30,331
All right, then, just you and me.

276
00:21:32,541 --> 00:21:36,420
You gonna come clean, then?
What's really in it for you?

277
00:21:36,545 --> 00:21:39,673
For me? Perhaps some peace.

278
00:21:40,382 --> 00:21:42,885
-From what?
-From her.

279
00:21:44,553 --> 00:21:47,973
Well, that's just a woman on the telly.
That's just a programme.

280
00:21:48,057 --> 00:21:50,601
What a pretty little girl.

281
00:21:51,644 --> 00:21:54,647
-Oh, my God. Are you talking to me?
-Yes.

282
00:21:54,730 --> 00:21:57,566
I'm talking to you, little one.

283
00:21:58,108 --> 00:22:01,904
Unseasonably chilly for the time of year,
don't you think?

284
00:22:02,905 --> 00:22:05,908
-What are you?
-I'm The Wire.

285
00:22:06,200 --> 00:22:10,579
And I'm hungry!

286
00:22:12,915 --> 00:22:14,625
Magpie, help me!

287
00:22:15,125 --> 00:22:17,753
Just think of that
audience tomorrow, my dear,

288
00:22:17,878 --> 00:22:20,756
all settling down to watch the Coronation.

289
00:22:20,840 --> 00:22:25,386
Twenty million people.
Things will never be the same again.

290
00:22:26,512 --> 00:22:29,014
I'm sorry. So sorry.

291
00:22:29,431 --> 00:22:30,683
Help me!

292
00:22:35,062 --> 00:22:37,940
Good night, children, everywhere.

293
00:22:39,275 --> 00:22:42,278
Start from the beginning.
Tell me everything you know.

294
00:22:42,653 --> 00:22:45,406
Well, for starters,

295
00:22:45,531 --> 00:22:47,950
I know you can't wrap your hand
round your elbow

296
00:22:48,075 --> 00:22:51,287
-and make your fingers meet.
-Don't get clever with me.

297
00:22:52,746 --> 00:22:56,625
You were there today at Florizel Street,
and now breaking into this establishment.

298
00:22:56,709 --> 00:22:59,837
Oh, you're connected with this.
Make no mistake.

299
00:22:59,920 --> 00:23:01,881
Well, the thing is,

300
00:23:01,964 --> 00:23:05,134
-Detective Inspector Bishop...
-How do you know my name?

301
00:23:05,259 --> 00:23:07,469
It's written inside your collar.

302
00:23:11,015 --> 00:23:13,726
Bless your mum. But I can't help thinking,

303
00:23:13,809 --> 00:23:18,814
Detective Inspector, you're not exactly
doing much detective-inspecting, are you?

304
00:23:18,939 --> 00:23:20,774
I'm doing everything in my power.

305
00:23:20,858 --> 00:23:24,653
All you're doing is grabbing those faceless
people and hiding them as fast as you can.

306
00:23:24,778 --> 00:23:27,072
Don't tell me, orders from above.

307
00:23:27,781 --> 00:23:30,409
Coronation Day, the eyes of the world
are on London Town,

308
00:23:30,492 --> 00:23:32,494
so any sort of problem
just gets swept out of sight.

309
00:23:32,578 --> 00:23:35,998
The nation has an image to maintain.

310
00:23:36,123 --> 00:23:38,417
But doesn't it drive you mad,
doing nothing?

311
00:23:38,500 --> 00:23:41,128
Don't you want
to get out there and investigate?

312
00:23:41,211 --> 00:23:43,047
Course I do.

313
00:23:43,130 --> 00:23:44,548
But...

314
00:23:47,009 --> 00:23:50,554
with all the crowds expected,
we haven't got the manpower.

315
00:23:50,679 --> 00:23:52,973
Even if we did,

316
00:23:53,098 --> 00:23:56,060
this is beyond anything we've ever seen.

317
00:23:58,604 --> 00:24:00,481
I just don't know anymore.

318
00:24:03,525 --> 00:24:07,988
Twenty years on the force,
I don't even know where to start.

319
00:24:08,072 --> 00:24:10,491
We haven't the faintest clue
what's going on.

320
00:24:10,574 --> 00:24:14,370
-Well, that could change.
-How?

321
00:24:18,082 --> 00:24:21,210
Start from the beginning.
Tell me everything you know.

322
00:24:37,977 --> 00:24:40,229
We started finding them
about a month ago.

323
00:24:40,354 --> 00:24:42,648
Persons left sans visage.

324
00:24:42,731 --> 00:24:45,150
Heads just...blank.

325
00:24:45,234 --> 00:24:46,986
Is there any sort of pattern?

326
00:24:47,069 --> 00:24:48,946
It's spreading out from North London,

327
00:24:49,029 --> 00:24:52,908
all over the city.
Men, women, kids, grannies.

328
00:24:52,992 --> 00:24:55,869
Only real lead is
there's been quite a large number in...

329
00:24:55,953 --> 00:24:57,579
Florizel Street.

330
00:24:57,705 --> 00:24:59,498
Found another one, sir.

331
00:24:59,581 --> 00:25:02,209
Oh, good man, Crabtree.
Here we are, Doctor.

332
00:25:03,168 --> 00:25:04,545
Take a good look.

333
00:25:05,087 --> 00:25:06,922
See what you can deduce.

334
00:25:08,257 --> 00:25:10,134
-Rose.
-You know her?

335
00:25:11,427 --> 00:25:13,429
Know her? She...

336
00:25:17,307 --> 00:25:21,103
They found her in the street apparently,
down by Damascus Road. Just abandoned.

337
00:25:21,228 --> 00:25:25,065
That's unusual. That's the first one
out in the open... (FADES OUT)

338
00:25:25,733 --> 00:25:28,902
...we'll have Torchwood
on our backs then, make no mistake.

339
00:25:28,986 --> 00:25:31,321
-They did what?
-I'm sorry?

340
00:25:32,239 --> 00:25:35,701
-They left her where?
-Just...in the street.

341
00:25:36,994 --> 00:25:39,246
In the street. They left her in the street.

342
00:25:39,329 --> 00:25:43,250
They took her face and just chucked her out
and left her in the street.

343
00:25:45,252 --> 00:25:47,629
And, as a result, that makes things...

344
00:25:48,964 --> 00:25:51,008
simple, very, very simple.

345
00:25:52,051 --> 00:25:54,219
-Do you know why?
-No.

346
00:25:54,303 --> 00:25:58,640
Because now, Detective Inspector Bishop,
there is no power on this Earth

347
00:25:58,766 --> 00:26:01,310
that can stop me! Come on!

348
00:26:06,857 --> 00:26:08,901
The big day dawns.

349
00:26:09,735 --> 00:26:12,529
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

350
00:26:14,490 --> 00:26:16,200
(DOOR CLOSING)

351
00:26:16,742 --> 00:26:19,078
You've had your fun with your little Doctor.

352
00:26:19,161 --> 00:26:23,207
But now you're left with me, Rita,
so you'll behave yourself.

353
00:26:23,874 --> 00:26:25,084
And smile.

354
00:26:27,753 --> 00:26:29,713
Here we go, everyone, here we go!

355
00:26:29,838 --> 00:26:33,634
Grub's up. Grub's up. Tuck in, everyone.
Tuck in. Take a sandwich.

356
00:26:33,717 --> 00:26:36,970
Oh, here we go, it's starting.
Look, look. Go and take your places.

357
00:26:37,054 --> 00:26:40,015
Sit down. Sit down. There we are.

358
00:26:40,140 --> 00:26:41,892
MAN: (ON TV) ...in front of the palace...

359
00:26:42,017 --> 00:26:46,855
WOMAN: Rita, love, just look at
that telly-box, then! Innit marvellous?

360
00:26:47,189 --> 00:26:49,191
The picture's so clear!

361
00:26:49,316 --> 00:26:52,402
Here, Bet, I says to Rita, I says,

362
00:26:52,528 --> 00:26:55,280
"You didn't need
to get your hair done special, love.

363
00:26:55,364 --> 00:26:58,200
"The Queen won't be able to see you!"

364
00:26:59,701 --> 00:27:02,955
Where's your old mum, then?
She can't go missing it.

365
00:27:03,163 --> 00:27:05,791
Sorry, Mum can't make it down.

366
00:27:05,874 --> 00:27:08,043
Aw, bless her.

367
00:27:08,335 --> 00:27:11,004
Maybe we could pop up and see her later.

368
00:27:11,130 --> 00:27:14,633
Maybe you could. It's a good idea.
What do you think, Dad?

369
00:27:14,716 --> 00:27:17,344
Maybe Aunty Betty can go
and see Gran later.

370
00:27:17,928 --> 00:27:20,472
Oh, he loves his Gran, this one.

371
00:27:20,722 --> 00:27:22,766
Proper little mummy's boy all round.

372
00:27:22,891 --> 00:27:25,477
Oh, you know what they say about them.

373
00:27:25,561 --> 00:27:27,855
Eddie, you want to beat that out of him.

374
00:27:27,938 --> 00:27:30,399
That's exactly what I'm gonna do.

375
00:27:31,150 --> 00:27:32,484
(DOORBELL RINGING)

376
00:27:32,568 --> 00:27:33,861
I'll get it.

377
00:27:33,944 --> 00:27:36,613
...will first appear
in about 10 minutes' time

378
00:27:36,738 --> 00:27:39,700
riding in the gold coach of state.

379
00:27:41,118 --> 00:27:42,661
Tommy, talk to me.

380
00:27:42,828 --> 00:27:45,956
I need to know exactly what happened
inside your house.

381
00:27:46,707 --> 00:27:49,209
-What the blazes do you think you're doing?
-I wanna help, Dad!

382
00:27:49,334 --> 00:27:52,713
-Mr Connolly.
-Shut your face, you.

383
00:27:52,963 --> 00:27:55,924
Whoever you are.
We can handle this ourselves!

384
00:27:58,010 --> 00:28:00,387
Listen, you little twerp.

385
00:28:00,971 --> 00:28:04,683
You're hardly out of the blooming cradle
so I don't expect you to understand,

386
00:28:04,766 --> 00:28:07,311
but I've got a position to maintain.

387
00:28:07,436 --> 00:28:09,730
People round here respect me.

388
00:28:09,938 --> 00:28:12,274
It matters what people think.

389
00:28:12,941 --> 00:28:14,860
Is that why you did it, Dad?

390
00:28:16,737 --> 00:28:18,822
What do you mean? Did what?

391
00:28:18,947 --> 00:28:20,365
You ratted on Gran.

392
00:28:20,449 --> 00:28:22,576
How else would the police know
where to look?

393
00:28:22,659 --> 00:28:24,411
Unless some coward told them.

394
00:28:24,494 --> 00:28:26,580
How dare you?

395
00:28:26,997 --> 00:28:31,960
You think I fought a war
just so a mouthy little scum like you

396
00:28:32,044 --> 00:28:33,837
could call me a coward!

397
00:28:34,087 --> 00:28:37,674
You don't get it, do you?
You fought against fascism, remember?

398
00:28:38,467 --> 00:28:41,553
People telling you how to live.
Who you could be friends with.

399
00:28:41,637 --> 00:28:45,432
Who you could fall in love with.
Who could live and who had to die.

400
00:28:45,557 --> 00:28:48,560
Don't you get it? You were fighting
so that little twerps like me

401
00:28:48,644 --> 00:28:51,188
could do what we want, say what we want.

402
00:28:51,313 --> 00:28:53,232
Now you've become just like them.

403
00:28:53,315 --> 00:28:55,442
You've been informing on everyone,
haven't you?

404
00:28:55,525 --> 00:28:59,112
Even Gran.
All to protect your precious reputation!

405
00:28:59,196 --> 00:29:02,324
Eddie, is that true?

406
00:29:02,407 --> 00:29:04,493
I did it for us, Rita.

407
00:29:05,160 --> 00:29:08,956
She was filthy! A filthy disgusting thing!

408
00:29:09,706 --> 00:29:11,458
She's my mother.

409
00:29:13,502 --> 00:29:17,673
All the others you informed on,
all the people in our street, our friends.

410
00:29:18,340 --> 00:29:19,675
I had to.

411
00:29:22,469 --> 00:29:23,887
I did the right thing.

412
00:29:24,012 --> 00:29:27,140
The right thing for us or for you, Eddie?

413
00:29:30,352 --> 00:29:31,812
You go, Tommy.

414
00:29:31,895 --> 00:29:34,147
Go with the Doctor and do some good.

415
00:29:34,231 --> 00:29:36,608
Get away from this house. It's poison.

416
00:29:37,651 --> 00:29:40,028
We've had a ruddy monster
under our roof all right,

417
00:29:40,153 --> 00:29:41,863
but it weren't my mother!

418
00:29:43,699 --> 00:29:44,950
EDDIE: Rita!

419
00:29:45,242 --> 00:29:46,702
Tommy.

420
00:29:55,544 --> 00:29:58,171
-What was all that, then?
-That was...

421
00:29:58,255 --> 00:30:00,841
That was the sound of something ending.

422
00:30:00,924 --> 00:30:03,802
And about time, too. Everyone all right?

423
00:30:03,885 --> 00:30:05,387
Smashing.

424
00:30:05,512 --> 00:30:08,056
Nothing's gonna spoil our big day, is it?

425
00:30:14,771 --> 00:30:18,066
Tommy, tell me about that night,
the night she changed.

426
00:30:18,150 --> 00:30:20,235
She was just watching the telly.

427
00:30:21,236 --> 00:30:24,614
Rose said it. She guessed it straightaway.
Of course she did.

428
00:30:24,698 --> 00:30:26,783
All these aerials in one little street.
How come?

429
00:30:26,908 --> 00:30:29,036
Bloke up the road, Mr Magpie,
he's selling them cheap.

430
00:30:29,119 --> 00:30:30,954
-Is he, now?
-Come on!

431
00:30:32,080 --> 00:30:34,041
BISHOP: Here! You can't do that.

432
00:30:34,124 --> 00:30:35,542
Shop!

433
00:30:36,877 --> 00:30:40,714
If you're here,
come out and talk to me, Magpie!

434
00:30:40,797 --> 00:30:42,883
-Maybe he's out.
-Looks like it.

435
00:30:45,844 --> 00:30:47,429
Oh, hello.

436
00:30:48,138 --> 00:30:51,516
This isn't right. This is very much not right.

437
00:30:54,269 --> 00:30:56,355
Tastes like iron. Bakelite.

438
00:30:56,521 --> 00:30:58,648
Knocked together with human hands, yes,

439
00:30:58,774 --> 00:31:00,359
but the design itself...

440
00:31:01,735 --> 00:31:04,946
Oh, beautiful work. That is so simple.

441
00:31:05,113 --> 00:31:08,450
That's incredible.
It's like a television, but portable.

442
00:31:08,700 --> 00:31:10,619
A portable television!

443
00:31:10,744 --> 00:31:13,372
It's not the only power source in this room.

444
00:31:27,928 --> 00:31:29,471
TOMMY: Gran.

445
00:31:43,068 --> 00:31:44,611
I'm on my way.

446
00:31:47,489 --> 00:31:49,491
What do you think you're doing?

447
00:31:50,617 --> 00:31:52,953
I want my friend restored
and I think that's beyond

448
00:31:53,036 --> 00:31:56,665
a little backstreet electrician, so tell me,
who's really in charge here?

449
00:31:56,748 --> 00:31:59,709
Yoo-hoo. I think that must be me.

450
00:32:00,585 --> 00:32:04,047
Oh, this one's smart as paint.

451
00:32:04,131 --> 00:32:05,590
Is she talking to us?

452
00:32:05,674 --> 00:32:08,635
I'm sorry, gentlemen, I'm afraid
you've brought this on yourselves.

453
00:32:08,718 --> 00:32:11,471
May I introduce you to my new friend.

454
00:32:11,555 --> 00:32:13,682
Jolly nice to meet you.

455
00:32:13,765 --> 00:32:16,518
Oh, my God, it's her.
That woman off the telly!

456
00:32:16,685 --> 00:32:19,062
-No. It's just using her image.
-What?

457
00:32:20,689 --> 00:32:22,899
-What are you?
-I'm The Wire.

458
00:32:23,733 --> 00:32:26,778
And I will gobble you up, pretty boy.

459
00:32:27,237 --> 00:32:29,448
Every last morsel!

460
00:32:29,531 --> 00:32:35,120
And when I have feasted,
I shall regain the corporeal body,

461
00:32:35,537 --> 00:32:37,956
which my fellow kind denied me.

462
00:32:38,290 --> 00:32:41,042
Good Lord. Colour television.

463
00:32:41,168 --> 00:32:44,838
-So your own people tried to stop you?
-They executed me,

464
00:32:44,921 --> 00:32:50,010
but I escaped in this form
and fled across the stars.

465
00:32:50,177 --> 00:32:52,971
And now you're trapped in the television.

466
00:32:53,597 --> 00:32:55,557
Not for much longer.

467
00:32:55,682 --> 00:32:57,767
Doctor, is this what got my gran?

468
00:32:57,851 --> 00:33:02,147
Yes, Tommy. It feeds off
the electrical activity of the brain,

469
00:33:02,230 --> 00:33:05,567
but it gorges itself
like a great, over-fed pig.

470
00:33:05,734 --> 00:33:08,945
Taking people's faces,
their essence as it stuffs itself.

471
00:33:09,196 --> 00:33:11,781
-And you let her do it, Magpie.
-I had to.

472
00:33:12,199 --> 00:33:13,658
She allowed me my face.

473
00:33:13,742 --> 00:33:16,870
She's promised to release me
at the time of manifestation.

474
00:33:16,953 --> 00:33:19,581
-What does that mean?
-The appointed time.

475
00:33:19,664 --> 00:33:21,541
My crowning glory.

476
00:33:21,625 --> 00:33:23,168
Doctor, the Coronation!

477
00:33:23,251 --> 00:33:27,339
For the first time in history,
millions gathered round a television set.

478
00:33:28,006 --> 00:33:30,926
But you're not strong enough yet, are you?

479
00:33:31,593 --> 00:33:33,553
You can't do it all from here.

480
00:33:34,179 --> 00:33:36,598
That's why you need this.

481
00:33:36,765 --> 00:33:38,600
You need something more powerful.

482
00:33:38,683 --> 00:33:42,103
This will turn a big transmitter
into a big receiver.

483
00:33:42,229 --> 00:33:44,648
What a clever thing you are.

484
00:33:45,357 --> 00:33:47,692
But why fret about it? Why not just relax?

485
00:33:47,776 --> 00:33:50,487
Kick off your shoes
and enjoy the Coronation.

486
00:33:50,612 --> 00:33:54,866
Believe me, you'll be glued to the screen.

487
00:33:58,203 --> 00:33:59,579
-Doctor!
-Hold on.

488
00:33:59,663 --> 00:34:01,164
Hungry!

489
00:34:01,498 --> 00:34:03,416
Hungry.

490
00:34:03,667 --> 00:34:08,797
The Wire is hungry! Oh, this one is tasty!

491
00:34:09,798 --> 00:34:14,344
Oh, I'll have lashings of him. Delicious!

492
00:34:14,803 --> 00:34:16,471
Ah!

493
00:34:16,555 --> 00:34:18,181
Armed?

494
00:34:18,306 --> 00:34:23,019
He's armed and clever.
Withdraw! Withdraw!

495
00:34:26,481 --> 00:34:29,484
The box, Magpie, the box!

496
00:34:33,405 --> 00:34:34,573
Hold tight!

497
00:34:36,658 --> 00:34:40,120
Conduct me to my victory, Magpie.

498
00:34:49,254 --> 00:34:52,841
Hungry! Hungry!

499
00:34:54,843 --> 00:34:56,845
Feed me/

500
00:34:57,429 --> 00:35:01,349
-Oh, she's so lovely!
-RITA: Beautiful.

501
00:35:01,766 --> 00:35:03,977
Makes you forget all your troubles.

502
00:35:04,978 --> 00:35:07,105
Everyone all right for pop?

503
00:35:14,779 --> 00:35:17,782
Tommy, wake up! Tommy, come on!

504
00:35:18,325 --> 00:35:21,161
-What happened?
-Where's Magpie?

505
00:35:23,038 --> 00:35:25,582
We don't even know where to start looking.
It's too late.

506
00:35:25,707 --> 00:35:28,835
Never too late, as a wise person once said.

507
00:35:28,918 --> 00:35:31,129
Kylie, I think. The Wire's got big plans.

508
00:35:31,212 --> 00:35:34,591
It'll need... Oh, yes, yes.
She's gonna harvest half the population.

509
00:35:34,716 --> 00:35:37,052
Millions and millions of people.
And where are we?

510
00:35:37,177 --> 00:35:40,764
-Muswell Hill.
-Muswell Hill. Muswell Hill! Which means...

511
00:35:41,890 --> 00:35:43,266
Alexandra Palace!

512
00:35:43,350 --> 00:35:45,644
Biggest TV transmitter
in North London. Oh!

513
00:35:45,727 --> 00:35:48,605
-What's why it chose this place, Tommy!
-What are you gonna do?

514
00:35:48,730 --> 00:35:50,732
I'm going shopping.

515
00:36:02,494 --> 00:36:04,037
This what you want?

516
00:36:06,039 --> 00:36:09,459
Perfect! Right, I need one more thing.

517
00:36:11,211 --> 00:36:13,630
(TYRES SCREECHING)

518
00:36:18,760 --> 00:36:20,845
Got it. Let's go.

519
00:36:34,317 --> 00:36:37,445
Her Majesty is wearing...

520
00:37:09,561 --> 00:37:11,104
I can't do this!

521
00:37:12,188 --> 00:37:14,441
Please! Please, don't make me.

522
00:37:14,524 --> 00:37:19,362
The time is at hand. Feed me!

523
00:37:19,696 --> 00:37:22,532
Feed me/

524
00:37:26,661 --> 00:37:27,871
There!

525
00:37:29,038 --> 00:37:30,290
Come on!

526
00:37:31,249 --> 00:37:34,794
Wait, wait, wait. Where do we think we...
Oh, I'm very sorry, sir.

527
00:37:34,878 --> 00:37:38,923
-Shouldn't you be at the Coronation?
-They're saving me a seat.

528
00:37:39,007 --> 00:37:42,218
-Who'd he think you were?
-King of Belgium apparently.

529
00:37:42,510 --> 00:37:44,971
(CROWD CHEERING ON TV)

530
00:37:45,263 --> 00:37:47,682
WOMAN: (ON TV) ...will wait there a while.

531
00:37:47,766 --> 00:37:52,812
But he will go on
ahead of Her Majesty into the Abbey...

532
00:37:53,229 --> 00:37:54,856
Keep this switched on.

533
00:37:55,690 --> 00:37:59,861
Don't let anyone stop you, Tommy.
Everything depends on it, you understand?

534
00:38:02,989 --> 00:38:05,700
MAN: (ON TV) Her Majesty moves across...

535
00:38:14,459 --> 00:38:19,172
You'll get yourself killed up there!
Your Majesty!

536
00:38:42,070 --> 00:38:45,281
Feed me/

537
00:38:47,992 --> 00:38:50,829
(LAUGHING)

538
00:39:12,350 --> 00:39:14,936
Ah! Feast!

539
00:39:15,436 --> 00:39:20,441
Feasting! The Wire is feasting!

540
00:39:28,741 --> 00:39:32,287
It's too late. It's too late for all of us!

541
00:39:32,453 --> 00:39:35,832
I shall consume you, Doctor!

542
00:39:41,421 --> 00:39:43,423
I won't let you do this, Magpie!

543
00:39:43,506 --> 00:39:46,467
Help me, Doctor! It burns!

544
00:39:47,218 --> 00:39:49,637
It took my face,

545
00:39:49,721 --> 00:39:51,431
my soul!

546
00:39:51,514 --> 00:39:56,019
You cannot stop The Wire.
Soon, I shall become manifest.

547
00:39:57,228 --> 00:39:59,314
(DOCTOR SCREAMING)

548
00:39:59,439 --> 00:40:04,402
No more. No more of this.
You promised me peace.

549
00:40:04,485 --> 00:40:07,488
Then peace you shall have.

550
00:40:08,615 --> 00:40:10,700
(MAGPIE SCREAMING)

551
00:40:18,708 --> 00:40:20,793
Been burning the candle at both ends?

552
00:40:20,877 --> 00:40:23,296
You've over-extended yourself, missus.

553
00:40:23,463 --> 00:40:26,674
You shouldn't have had a crack
at poor old Magpie there.

554
00:40:28,051 --> 00:40:29,594
(EXCLAIMING)

555
00:40:32,847 --> 00:40:35,850
Rubber soles, swear by them.

556
00:40:43,524 --> 00:40:48,613
Oh, dear. Has our little plan
gone horribly wrong, Doctor?

557
00:40:57,872 --> 00:41:02,877
...coat of shimmering cloth of gold
lined with a crimson silk...

558
00:41:05,964 --> 00:41:08,091
(ON TV) ...are you willing to do the same?

559
00:41:11,886 --> 00:41:14,639
No!

560
00:41:27,402 --> 00:41:30,738
It's closed down, I'm afraid,
and no epilogue.

561
00:41:30,947 --> 00:41:33,658
(THE WIRE SCREAMING)

562
00:41:41,249 --> 00:41:43,835
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

563
00:41:51,300 --> 00:41:53,594
(GOD SAVE THE QUEEN PLAYING ON TV)

564
00:41:55,304 --> 00:41:58,516
-What have I missed?
-Doctor! What happened?

565
00:41:58,599 --> 00:42:02,270
Sorted. Electrical creature. TV technology.

566
00:42:02,437 --> 00:42:04,605
Clever alien life form.

567
00:42:04,731 --> 00:42:07,984
That's me, by the way. I turned the receiver
back into a transmitter

568
00:42:08,109 --> 00:42:10,486
and I trapped The Wire in here.

569
00:42:11,654 --> 00:42:14,615
I just invented the home video
30 years early.

570
00:42:16,451 --> 00:42:17,785
Betamax.

571
00:42:18,786 --> 00:42:20,246
Oh, look!

572
00:42:20,538 --> 00:42:23,207
God save the Queen, eh?

573
00:42:31,632 --> 00:42:34,302
(PEOPLE CHEERING ON TV)

574
00:42:47,565 --> 00:42:52,612
Here's my grandson. Oh, son!
Oh, my goodness.

575
00:43:11,506 --> 00:43:15,218
This was never your house.
It's in my mother's name.

576
00:43:16,677 --> 00:43:19,472
And on her behalf, I'm telling you,

577
00:43:19,555 --> 00:43:20,890
out.

578
00:43:32,235 --> 00:43:33,486
(DOOR CLOSING)

579
00:43:33,694 --> 00:43:36,364
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

580
00:43:52,171 --> 00:43:54,549
We could go down the Mall,
join in with the crowds.

581
00:43:54,674 --> 00:43:57,468
No, that's just pomp and circumstance.

582
00:43:57,552 --> 00:44:00,721
-This is history, right here.
-The domestic approach?

583
00:44:00,847 --> 00:44:02,557
DOCTOR: Exactly.

584
00:44:03,099 --> 00:44:07,436
Will it... That thing...
is it trapped for good on the video?

585
00:44:07,520 --> 00:44:08,729
Hope so.

586
00:44:08,813 --> 00:44:11,315
Just to be on the safe side, though,
I'll use my unrivalled knowledge

587
00:44:11,399 --> 00:44:15,194
of trans-temporal extirpation methods to
neutralise the residual electronic pattern.

588
00:44:15,278 --> 00:44:17,405
-You what?
-I'm going to tape over it.

589
00:44:17,530 --> 00:44:20,158
Just leave it to me. I'm always doing that.

590
00:44:20,241 --> 00:44:22,827
Tell you what, Tommy.
You can have the scooter. Little present.

591
00:44:22,910 --> 00:44:26,080
Best keep it in the garage
for a few years, though, eh?

592
00:44:27,957 --> 00:44:29,584
Good riddance.

593
00:44:32,420 --> 00:44:34,130
Is that it, then, Tommy?

594
00:44:35,173 --> 00:44:37,425
New monarch, new age, new world.

595
00:44:37,884 --> 00:44:40,720
-No room for a man like Eddie Connolly.
-That's right.

596
00:44:40,803 --> 00:44:42,555
He deserves it.

597
00:44:44,265 --> 00:44:46,100
Tommy, go after him.

598
00:44:46,601 --> 00:44:48,895
-What for?
-He's your dad.

599
00:44:49,270 --> 00:44:52,607
-He's an idiot.
-Course he is. Like I said, he's your dad.

600
00:44:53,608 --> 00:44:55,568
But you're clever,

601
00:44:55,651 --> 00:44:58,446
clever enough to save the world
so don't stop there.

602
00:45:00,489 --> 00:45:01,949
Go on.

603
00:45:42,281 --> 00:45:45,743
We've gone beyond the reach of
the Tardis' knowledge. Not a good move.

604
00:45:46,786 --> 00:45:48,079
Entering Nightshift.

605
00:45:48,162 --> 00:45:50,748
This writing is old.

606
00:45:50,831 --> 00:45:52,208
Impossibly old.

607
00:45:52,708 --> 00:45:55,920
-People! Look at that, real people.
-That's us. Hooray!

608
00:45:56,003 --> 00:45:58,673
The Beast and his armies
shall rise from the pit...

609
00:46:00,508 --> 00:46:03,177
Whatever it is down there,
it's not a natural phenomenon.

610
00:46:03,386 --> 00:46:05,471
We could revolutionise modern science.

611
00:46:05,554 --> 00:46:07,807
We could use it to fuel the empire.

612
00:46:07,890 --> 00:46:09,725
Or start a war.

613
00:46:09,809 --> 00:46:12,979
-That's a black hole.
-But that's impossible.

